"# Chapter 6: Harmony

**intervals, triads, chords, cadence**

---

Twinkle Twinkle now has shape — you've learned melody, phrasing, rhythm, meter. But play the tune alone and something is missing. Music gains depth when pitches sound *together*, when one note's presence changes the color of another. That's **harmony**.

We call it harmony, but we're really dealing with *simultaneous sound* — the way frequencies combine, reinforce, and color one another. A melody is a line through pitch-time; harmony is the vertical dimension, the sounding *now* of multiple pitches at once.

This chapter teaches:

- **Intervals** — the distance between two pitches, the smallest harmonic unit.
- **Triads** — three-note chords, the building blocks of tonal harmony.
- **Chords** — how to voice and schedule them in Scheme.
- **Cadence** — harmonic motion that gives music direction and rest.

By the end, you'll harmonize Twinkle Twinkle — melody with a bassline and chords underneath.

---

## 6.1 The Interval — Two Pitches, One Relationship

An **interval** is the distance between two pitches, measured in **semitones** (the smallest step on a piano keyboard, one key to the next). Play two notes together or in sequence and you've made an interval.

`[VISUAL: piano keyboard segment, C to G marked — 7 semitones, labeled \"perfect fifth\"]`

A perfect fifth (7 semitones, e.g., C to G) sounds stable, open, familiar. A minor second (1 semitone, e.g., C to C♯) sounds tight, dissonant, uneasy. Intervals have *character* — they color the music.

**Common intervals** (from the root C, ascending):

| Name | Semitones | Example pitches | Character |
|------|-----------|-----------------|-----------|
| unison | 0 | C – C | identical |
| minor 2nd | 1 | C – C♯ | tense |
| major 2nd | 2 | C – D | stepwise, melodic |
| minor 3rd | 3 | C – E♭ | darker, minor-flavored |
| major 3rd | 4 | C – E | brighter, major-flavored |
| perfect 4th | 5 | C – F | stable, open |
| tritone | 6 | C – F♯ | restless, \"the devil's interval\" |
| perfect 5th | 7 | C – G | very stable, foundational |
| minor 6th | 8 | C – A♭ | warm, yearning |
| major 6th | 9 | C – A | open, sweet |
| minor 7th | 10 | C – B♭ | jazzy, unresolved |
| major 7th | 11 | C – B | bright, leading upward |
| octave | 12 | C – C' | the \"same\" pitch, doubled |

Let's play a few:

```scheme
;; A perfect fifth: C4 and G4 sounding together
(define (fifth)
  (note/strike 'c4 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g4 'quarter 0.7))

(fifth)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire fifth example → two simultaneous quarter notes, C4 + G4, default piano voice -->`

You hear both pitches at once. The interval is consonant — the frequencies lock into a simple ratio (3:2), so the combined sound is stable.

Now a minor second:

```scheme
;; A minor second: C4 and C♯4
(define (minor-second)
  (note/strike 'c4 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'c#4 'quarter 0.7))

(minor-second)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire minor-second example → two simultaneous quarter notes, C4 + C♯4 -->`

Tense, crunchy. The frequencies are very close (ratio near 16:15), so they \"beat\" against each other. That tension is useful — it *wants* to move somewhere.

`[VISUAL: waveform of C4+G4 (stable, regular) vs. C4+C♯4 (beating interference pattern)]`

---

## 6.2 The Triad — Three Notes, One Chord

A **triad** is a three-note chord built by stacking intervals of a third. The most common triads are **major** and **minor**.

A **major triad** = root + major 3rd + perfect 5th (e.g., C–E–G, 0–4–7 semitones).  
A **minor triad** = root + minor 3rd + perfect 5th (e.g., C–E♭–G, 0–3–7 semitones).

Major triads sound bright, open, resolved. Minor triads sound darker, sadder, introspective. The difference is one note — the third.

`[VISUAL: staff notation, treble clef: C major triad (C–E–G) and C minor triad (C–E♭–G) side by side]`

Let's play them:

```scheme
;; C major triad
(define (c-major)
  (note/strike 'c4 'half 0.7)
  (note/strike 'e4 'half 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g4 'half 0.7))

(c-major)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire c-major example → three simultaneous half notes, C4+E4+G4 -->`

Now minor:

```scheme
;; C minor triad
(define (c-minor)
  (note/strike 'c4 'half 0.7)
  (note/strike 'eb4 'half 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g4 'half 0.7))

(c-minor)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire c-minor example → three simultaneous half notes, C4+E♭4+G4 -->`

The difference is subtle but fundamental. That one lowered note (E to E♭) shifts the entire color of the chord.

`[VISUAL: spectrum comparison — C major vs. C minor triad, showing the shifted third harmonic]`

### Building triads from any root

You can build a major triad from any pitch. The formula is always the same: root, +4 semitones, +7 semitones.

Here's a helper that builds a major triad from a given root pitch:

```scheme
;; Build a major triad from a root pitch (simplified — no semitone arithmetic yet)
;; We define the triads by hand for common roots:

(define (triad-major root dur vel)
  (cond
    ((eq? root 'c4)
     (begin
       (note/strike 'c4 dur vel)
       (note/strike 'e4 dur vel)
       (note/strike 'g4 dur vel)))
    ((eq? root 'f4)
     (begin
       (note/strike 'f4 dur vel)
       (note/strike 'a4 dur vel)
       (note/strike 'c5 dur vel)))
    ((eq? root 'g4)
     (begin
       (note/strike 'g4 dur vel)
       (note/strike 'b4 dur vel)
       (note/strike 'd5 dur vel)))
    (else
     (note/strike root dur vel)))) ;; fallback: just the root

;; Play a few common triads:
(triad-major 'c4 'half 0.7)
(triad-major 'f4 'half 0.7)
(triad-major 'g4 'half 0.7)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire triad-major example → three chords in sequence, each sounding as a three-note simultaneity, C major, F major, G major -->`

This is a manual lookup — we haven't taught pitch arithmetic yet. But the idea is clear: a triad is a defined *structure*, and you can summon it from any root.

`[VISUAL: staff notation, three triads in sequence: C major, F major, G major, whole notes]`

---

## 6.3 Chords in Time — Voicing and Rhythm

A chord is a simultaneity — multiple pitches at the same time-point. But chords also have **voicing** (which notes go where) and **rhythm** (when they sound, how long they last).

You've already seen the simplest voicing: all notes strike together, same duration. But chords can be **broken** (arpeggiated, notes in sequence) or **sustained** (held underneath a melody).

### Arpeggiated chords

An arpeggio is a chord played one note at a time. Twinkle's opening melody (C C G G A A G) can be harmonized with a broken C major triad in the left hand:

```scheme
;; Twinkle melody (first phrase) with arpeggiated C major triad bass
(define (twinkle-with-arp)
  ;; Melody (right hand)
  (note/strike 'c5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'c5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'a5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'a5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'half 0.7)
  
  ;; Bass: arpeggiated C major triad (left hand, lower octave)
  (note/strike 'c3 'eighth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'e3 'eighth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'g3 'eighth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'c4 'eighth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'e3 'eighth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'g3 'eighth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'c4 'eighth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'e3 'eighth 0.6))

(twinkle-with-arp)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire twinkle-with-arp example → melody line + bass arpeggio, both scheduled, overlapping in time per the quarter/eighth durations -->`

`[VISUAL: two-staff score (treble + bass clefs): Twinkle melody top staff, arpeggiated C–E–G–C bass pattern bottom staff, bar 1–2]`

The melody and bass play *at the same time* — they overlap. The arpeggio fills the texture without cluttering the melody.

### Block chords (sustained)

A block chord is all notes struck together, held. This is the classic \"piano accompaniment\" shape:

```scheme
;; Twinkle first phrase with block chord accompaniment
(define (twinkle-with-chords)
  ;; Melody
  (note/strike 'c5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'c5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'a5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'a5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'half 0.7)
  
  ;; Harmony: C major triad, whole note (sustains under the phrase)
  (note/strike 'c3 'whole 0.5)
  (note/strike 'e3 'whole 0.5)
  (note/strike 'g3 'whole 0.5))

(twinkle-with-chords)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire twinkle-with-chords example → melody quarters + simultaneous whole-note triad in bass, chord sustains underneath -->`

`[VISUAL: two-staff score: melody (Twinkle first phrase) top staff, C major triad (whole note) bottom staff, aligned to bar 1]`

The chord sustains for the full measure (or longer). The melody moves above it. This is the texture of a hymn, a folk song, a simple piano piece.

---

## 6.4 Harmonic Progression — Chords in Motion

Harmony gains meaning when chords *move* — one chord to the next. A sequence of chords is a **harmonic progression**, and certain progressions feel like \"going somewhere\" while others feel like \"arriving.\"

The simplest and most powerful progression in Western music is **I – IV – V – I** (tonic, subdominant, dominant, tonic). In the key of C major:

- **I** = C major (C–E–G)
- **IV** = F major (F–A–C)
- **V** = G major (G–B–D)

Play them in sequence:

```scheme
;; I – IV – V – I progression in C major
(define (progression-i-iv-v-i)
  ;; I (C major)
  (note/strike 'c4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'e4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'g4 'whole 0.6)
  
  ;; IV (F major)
  (note/strike 'f4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'a4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'c5 'whole 0.6)
  
  ;; V (G major)
  (note/strike 'g4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'b4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'd5 'whole 0.6)
  
  ;; I (C major, return home)
  (note/strike 'c4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'e4 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'g4 'whole 0.6))

(progression-i-iv-v-i)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire progression-i-iv-v-i example → four chords in sequence, each a whole-note triad, I–IV–V–I in C major -->`

`[VISUAL: staff notation, bass clef, four whole-note triads: C major, F major, G major, C major, bar numbers 1–4]`

You hear a journey: the IV chord moves *away* from home, the V chord builds tension (it wants to resolve), and the final I chord brings you back. This motion — tension and release — is the engine of tonal harmony.

### Cadence

A **cadence** is a harmonic \"punctuation mark\" — a chord progression that signals a phrase ending. The strongest cadence is **V – I** (dominant to tonic), called an **authentic cadence**. It sounds like \"the end.\"

```scheme
;; Authentic cadence: V – I
(define (cadence-v-i)
  ;; V (G major)
  (note/strike 'g3 'half 0.6)
  (note/strike 'b3 'half 0.6)
  (note/strike 'd4 'half 0.6)
  
  ;; I (C major)
  (note/strike 'c3 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'e3 'whole 0.6)
  (note/strike 'g3 'whole 0.6))

(cadence-v-i)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire cadence-v-i example → two chords, G major half notes → C major whole notes -->`

That G major chord *pulls* toward C major. The B in G major (the leading tone) wants to rise to C; the D wants to fall to C or stay as E. The resolution is visceral.

Other common cadences:

- **Half cadence** (anything → V): ends on the dominant, feels \"unfinished.\"
- **Plagal cadence** (IV → I): the \"Amen\" cadence, softer, less forceful.
- **Deceptive cadence** (V → vi): expects I, lands on vi (A minor in C major), a surprise.

`[VISUAL: staff notation, four short progressions, each two chords, labeled: authentic (V–I), half (I–V), plagal (IV–I), deceptive (V–vi)]`

---

## 6.5 Harmonizing a Melody

Now we bring it together: **harmonizing Twinkle Twinkle** — melody plus bass plus chords.

Twinkle's first phrase (C C G G A A G) sits comfortably over a C major harmony. The second phrase (F F E E D D C) moves to F major, then back to C. A simple harmonization:

| Melody notes | Harmony | Roman numeral |
|--------------|---------|---------------|
| C C G G A A G | C major | I |
| F F E E D D C | F major → C major | IV → I |

Here's a fuller version with melody, bassline, and chords:

```scheme
;; Twinkle Twinkle, first two phrases, with harmony
(define (twinkle-harmonized)
  ;; Phrase 1: C C G G A A G (over C major)
  ;; Melody
  (note/strike 'c5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'c5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'a5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'a5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'g5 'half 0.7)
  
  ;; Bass (root movement: C for 2 bars)
  (note/strike 'c3 'whole 0.5)
  (note/strike 'c3 'whole 0.5)
  
  ;; Chords (C major triad, sustained)
  (note/strike 'e3 'whole 0.4)
  (note/strike 'g3 'whole 0.4)
  (note/strike 'e3 'whole 0.4)
  (note/strike 'g3 'whole 0.4)
  
  ;; Phrase 2: F F E E D D C (over F major → C major)
  ;; Melody
  (note/strike 'f5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'f5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'e5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'e5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'd5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'd5 'quarter 0.7)
  (note/strike 'c5 'half 0.7)
  
  ;; Bass (F → C)
  (note/strike 'f3 'whole 0.5)
  (note/strike 'c3 'whole 0.5)
  
  ;; Chords (F major → C major)
  (note/strike 'a3 'whole 0.4)
  (note/strike 'c4 'whole 0.4)
  (note/strike 'e3 'whole 0.4)
  (note/strike 'g3 'whole 0.4))

(twinkle-harmonized)
```

`<!-- BUILD: wire twinkle-harmonized example → full harmonization, three layers (melody/bass/chords) overlapping in time, scheduled correctly per durations -->`

`[VISUAL: grand staff (treble + bass), bars 1–4: melody top staff, bass notes (C, C, F, C) bottom staff, chord tones filled in between]`

You now hear **depth**. The melody is supported, the bass anchors the harmony, the chords fill the space. This is the texture of a hymn, a folk arrangement, a beginner piano piece.

