## Reaching for What You Don't Know — Anchoring Harmony in a Movement

Chord choices carry the fingerprint of a tradition. A ii–V–I lives inside bebop; a plagal cadence lives inside sacred choral music; a modal vamp lives inside cool jazz. When you write a progression, reaching for the movement atom lets you *name* the influence — not to show off, but so the operator understands where the sound is coming from.

### Choosing a cadence with the tradition in view

You want a resolving cadence with a specific flavor. Reach for the movement, then pick the cadence that fits.

```scheme
;; Play a ii-V-I and cite the tradition it belongs to.
(define (chord root quality dur)
  (case quality
    ((maj) (note root dur 60) (note 'E4 dur 60) (note 'G4 dur 60))
    ((min) (note root dur 60) (note 'Eb4 dur 60) (note 'G4 dur 60))
    ((dom7) (note root dur 60) (note 'E4 dur 60) (note 'G4 dur 60) (note 'Bb4 dur 60))))

(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'bebop)))
  (chord 'D4 'min 'quarter)
  (chord 'G4 'dom7 'quarter)
  (chord 'C4 'maj 'half)
  (motoi/say \"That ii-V-I is the beating heart of bebop harmony.\"))
```

Teaches: cite the tradition when you use its cadence; the reach carries the *why*.

### A plagal cadence with a sacred-music anchor

The IV–I \"amen\" cadence has a specific home. Reach for the movement, play the cadence, and hand the operator the connection.

```scheme
;; F-major to C-major — the plagal cadence.
(define (triad root third fifth dur)
  (note root dur 55)
  (note third dur 55)
  (note fifth dur 55))

(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'baroque)))
  (triad 'F4 'A4 'C5 'whole)
  (triad 'C4 'E4 'G4 'whole)
  (motoi/say \"IV to I — the amen cadence. Baroque sacred music leaned on it hard.\"))
```

Teaches: same reach shape, different movement — the code above the reach doesn't change.

### Modal vamps and the license to not resolve

Modal jazz lets you sit on a chord instead of leaving it. When the progression refuses to move, the movement atom is your explanation.

```scheme
(define (dorian-vamp measures)
  (let loop ((n measures))
    (when (> n 0)
      (note 'D4 'whole 60) (note 'F4 'whole 60) (note 'A4 'whole 60)
      (loop (- n 1)))))

(let ((atom (world/knowledge :movement 'modal-jazz)))
  (dorian-vamp 4)
  (motoi/say \"Four bars on D dorian — no chord change. Modal jazz says that's fine.\"))
```

Teaches: the reach lets you defend a static-harmony choice.


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### 6.1 Intervals — the distance between two pitches

An **interval** is the musical distance between two pitches. We name intervals by counting scale steps (a *second*, a *third*, a *fifth*) and by their quality (*major*, *minor*, *perfect*, *augmented*, *diminished*).

Here are the **perfect** intervals — they sound stable and open, because their frequency ratios are simple whole-number fractions:

```scheme
;; Perfect unison (1:1 — same pitch)
(define (play-unison)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80))

(play-unison)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays two C4s at once (unison) -->

```scheme
;; Perfect fifth (3:2 ratio — very consonant)
(define (play-fifth)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'G4 'half 80))

(play-fifth)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and G4 together (a perfect fifth) -->

The fifth sounds **open** and **stable**. Most folk music and rock power chords are built on fifths.

```scheme
;; Perfect fourth (4:3 ratio)
(define (play-fourth)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'half 80))

(play-fourth)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and F4 (a perfect fourth) -->

```scheme
;; Perfect octave (2:1 ratio — the same pitch class, one register apart)
(define (play-octave)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'C5 'half 80))

(play-octave)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and C5 (octave) -->

[VISUAL: staff showing C4–C5 octave, C4–G4 fifth, C4–F4 fourth, labeled with interval names and frequency ratios]

---

Now the **major and minor thirds** — these define the *color* of a chord (bright/happy vs. dark/sad):

```scheme
;; Major third (5:4 ratio, approximately)
(define (play-major-third)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'half 80))

(play-major-third)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and E4 (major third) -->

```scheme
;; Minor third (6:5 ratio, approximately)
(define (play-minor-third)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'Eb4 'half 80))

(play-minor-third)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and Eb4 (minor third) -->

The major third sounds **bright**. The minor third sounds **darker**, more introspective. That one semitone difference (E vs. Eb) changes the emotional character completely.

[VISUAL: staff showing C4–E4 (major third) and C4–Eb4 (minor third), side by side]

---

**Dissonant intervals** — these sound tense and ask to *resolve* to a consonance:

```scheme
;; Major second (9:8 — mildly dissonant)
(define (play-major-second)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 80))

(play-major-second)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and D4 (major second) -->

```scheme
;; Minor second (16:15 — very dissonant, a semitone)
(define (play-minor-second)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'Db4 'half 80))

(play-minor-second)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and Db4 (minor second, the most dissonant common interval) -->

The minor second is **crunchy** — it wants to resolve outward or collapse inward.

```scheme
;; Tritone (the \"devil's interval\" — 45:32, the most unstable)
(define (play-tritone)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'Gb4 'half 80))

(play-tritone)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C4 and Gb4 (tritone) -->

The tritone is **maximally ambiguous** — it divides the octave exactly in half and wants to resolve, but it's not obvious *which way*. Medieval music theorists called it *diabolus in musica* (the devil in music). Modern jazz loves it.

[VISUAL: staff showing C4–Db4 (minor second) and C4–Gb4 (tritone), labeled \"dissonant intervals\"]

---


### 6.2 Triads — stacking thirds

A **triad** is three pitches stacked in thirds. The lowest pitch is the **root**, the middle is the **third**, the top is the **fifth**. The *quality* of the thirds (major or minor) determines the triad's *type*.

**Major triad** — root, major third, perfect fifth (M3 + m3 stacked):

```scheme
(define (play-C-major-triad)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G4 'whole 80))

(play-C-major-triad)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C major triad (C–E–G) -->

Bright, stable, the sound of **resolution**.

[VISUAL: staff showing C major triad (C4–E4–G4) with labels: root, major 3rd, perfect 5th]

---

**Minor triad** — root, minor third, perfect fifth (m3 + M3 stacked):

```scheme
(define (play-C-minor-triad)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'Eb4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G4 'whole 80))

(play-C-minor-triad)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C minor triad (C–Eb–G) -->

Darker, introspective, still stable but **sad**.

[VISUAL: staff showing C minor triad (C4–Eb4–G4)]

---

**Diminished triad** — root, minor third, diminished fifth (m3 + m3):

```scheme
(define (play-B-diminished-triad)
  (note/strike 'B3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'whole 80))

(play-B-diminished-triad)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays B diminished triad (B–D–F) -->

**Tense**, unstable — that diminished fifth (a tritone above the root) wants to resolve inward.

[VISUAL: staff showing B diminished triad (B3–D4–F4), labeled \"contains a tritone (B–F)\"]

---

**Augmented triad** — root, major third, augmented fifth (M3 + M3):

```scheme
(define (play-C-augmented-triad)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'Ab4 'whole 80))

(play-C-augmented-triad)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C augmented triad (C–E–G#) -->

**Strange**, shimmery, floating — the augmented fifth wants to resolve *outward*.

[VISUAL: staff showing C augmented triad (C4–E4–G#4)]

---


### 6.3 Seventh chords — adding the fourth voice

A **seventh chord** adds one more third on top of a triad, making a four-note stack. The most common types:

**Dominant seventh** — major triad + minor seventh (the chord that *wants* to resolve to tonic):

```scheme
(define (play-G7)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'whole 80))

(play-G7)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays G7 (G–B–D–F) -->

G7 wants to resolve to C major. That F (the seventh) is a dissonance that pulls down to E, and the B (the third) pulls up to C. This is the **engine of tonal harmony**.

[VISUAL: staff showing G7 chord (G3–B3–D4–F4) with arrows showing F→E and B→C resolution tendencies]

---

**Major seventh** — major triad + major seventh:

```scheme
(define (play-Cmaj7)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'B4 'whole 80))

(play-Cmaj7)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays Cmaj7 (C–E–G–B) -->

**Dreamy**, lush, the sound of jazz ballads and bossa nova.

---

**Minor seventh** — minor triad + minor seventh:

```scheme
(define (play-Dm7)
  (note/strike 'D4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'A4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'C5 'whole 80))

(play-Dm7)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays Dm7 (D–F–A–C) -->

Smooth, mellow, the **ii7** chord in C major (we'll see why that matters in a moment).

---

**Diminished seventh** — diminished triad + diminished seventh:

```scheme
(define (play-Bdim7)
  (note/strike 'B3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'Ab4 'whole 80))

(play-Bdim7)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays Bdim7 (B–D–F–Ab) -->

**Extremely tense** — every interval is a minor third, so the chord is symmetrical and can resolve in multiple directions. Classical composers use it for drama; jazz uses it as a chromatic passing chord.

[VISUAL: staff showing all four seventh-chord types side by side: G7, Cmaj7, Dm7, Bdim7]

---


### 6.4 Cadence — how chords move

A **cadence** is a harmonic goal: a sequence of chords that creates expectation and then satisfies (or denies) it. The most important cadence in Western tonal music is the **authentic cadence**: **V → I** (dominant to tonic).

```scheme
;; Authentic cadence in C major: G7 → C
(define (authentic-cadence)
  ;; V7 (G7)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'half 80)
  
  ;; I (C major)
  (note/strike 'C3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80))

(authentic-cadence)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays V7–I cadence in C major -->

That sounds like **arrival**. The tension of the G7 resolves to the stability of C.

[VISUAL: staff showing V7→I progression in C major, with voice-leading arrows (F→E, B→C, D→C, G→C)]

---

**Plagal cadence** — **IV → I** (the \"Amen\" cadence):

```scheme
(define (plagal-cadence)
  ;; IV (F major)
  (note/strike 'F3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  
  ;; I (C major)
  (note/strike 'C3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 80))

(plagal-cadence)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays IV–I cadence (plagal) -->

Softer, gentler resolution — the sound of hymn endings.

---

**Half cadence** — ending on **V** (the dominant) instead of I — creates **expectation** but *no resolution*:

```scheme
(define (half-cadence)
  ;; I (C major)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'G4 'half 80)
  
  ;; V (G major)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'whole 80))

(half-cadence)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays I–V half cadence -->

It feels **unfinished** — like a question asked but not answered.

---

**Deceptive cadence** — **V → vi** (the chord you *expect* to be I turns out to be vi):

```scheme
(define (deceptive-cadence)
  ;; V (G major)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 80)
  
  ;; vi (A minor — surprise!)
  (note/strike 'A3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'whole 80))

(deceptive-cadence)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays V–vi deceptive cadence -->

**Unexpected** — your ear wanted C major, but got A minor instead. Composers use this to extend a phrase or delay resolution.

[VISUAL: staff showing all four cadence types: V–I (authentic), IV–I (plagal), I–V (half), V–vi (deceptive)]

---


### 6.5 Basslines — the foundation voice

The **bass** is the lowest voice, and it anchors the harmony. Even if the upper voices are doing complex things, a strong bass line makes the harmony *clear*.

A simple **root-position** bass just plays the root of each chord:

```scheme
(define (root-position-bass)
  ;; I (C)
  (note/strike 'C2 'quarter 90)
  
  ;; IV (F)
  (note/strike 'F2 'quarter 90)
  
  ;; V (G)
  (note/strike 'G2 'quarter 90)
  
  ;; I (C)
  (note/strike 'C2 'quarter 90))

(root-position-bass)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays a root-position bass line (I–IV–V–I) -->

Clear and direct.

---

A **walking bass** moves stepwise between chord tones:

```scheme
(define (walking-bass)
  ;; I (C) → approach IV
  (note/strike 'C2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'D2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'E2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'F2 'eighth 80)
  
  ;; IV (F) → approach V
  (note/strike 'F2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'G2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'B2 'eighth 80)
  
  ;; V (G) → back to I
  (note/strike 'G2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'F2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'E2 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'D2 'eighth 80)
  
  ;; I (C)
  (note/strike 'C2 'quarter 90))

(walking-bass)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays a walking bass line -->

More motion, more *momentum* — the sound of swing and stride piano.

---

A **pedal bass** holds one pitch while the harmony changes above it:

```scheme
(define (pedal-bass)
  ;; Pedal C in the bass, harmony changes above
  (note/strike 'C2 'whole 90)  ;; pedal tone (sustained)
  
  ;; Upper voices change chords
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 70)  ;; I
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 70)
  
  (note/strike 'F4 'quarter 70)  ;; IV over C pedal
  (note/strike 'A4 'quarter 70)
  
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 70)  ;; V over C pedal
  (note/strike 'B4 'quarter 70)
  
  (note/strike 'C5 'quarter 70)) ;; back to I

(pedal-bass)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays a C pedal while upper harmony shifts -->

Creates **tension** — the unchanging bass against moving chords.

[VISUAL: staff showing three bass-line styles: root-position, walking, pedal]

---


### 6.6 Voicing — how you space the chord matters

The same chord can sound very different depending on **how you space the pitches**. That's called **voicing**.

**Close voicing** — all the pitches within an octave:

```scheme
(define (close-voicing)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G4 'whole 80))

(close-voicing)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; C major triad in close position -->

Compact, clear, good for mid-range melody instruments.

---

**Open voicing** — spread the pitches across more than an octave:

```scheme
(define (open-voicing)
  (note/strike 'C3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'whole 80))

(open-voicing)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; C major triad in open position -->

**Airier**, more space between the voices — the sound of big-band jazz and orchestral writing.

---

**Drop-2 voicing** — take the second-highest note and drop it an octave:

```scheme
(define (drop-2-voicing)
  ;; Close: C4–E4–G4–B4 (Cmaj7)
  ;; Drop-2: C4–G3–E4–B4 (drop the G down)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 80)  ;; dropped
  (note/strike 'E4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'B4 'whole 80))

(drop-2-voicing)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; Cmaj7 in drop-2 voicing -->

A jazz piano/guitar staple — smoother voice-leading, easier to play.

---

**Quartal voicing** — stack fourths instead of thirds:

```scheme
(define (quartal-voicing)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'whole 80)  ;; fourth above C
  (note/strike 'Bb4 'whole 80) ;; fourth above F
  (note/strike 'Eb5 'whole 80)) ;; fourth above Bb

(quartal-voicing)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; quartal voicing (stacked fourths) -->

**Modern**, open, ambiguous — the sound of McCoy Tyner, Bill Evans, contemporary film scores.

[VISUAL: staff showing four voicing types side-by-side: close, open, drop-2, quartal]

---


### 6.7 Chord progressions — sequences that tell a story

A **progression** is a series of chords that creates motion and direction. Some progressions are so common they have names.

**I–IV–V–I** — the most fundamental progression in Western music:

```scheme
(define (I-IV-V-I)
  ;; I (C major)
  (note/strike 'C3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  
  ;; IV (F major)
  (note/strike 'F3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  
  ;; V (G major)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 80)
  
  ;; I (C major)
  (note/strike 'C3 'whole 90)
  (note/strike 'E3 'whole 90)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 90))

(I-IV-V-I)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays I–IV–V–I in C major -->

Thousands of folk songs, hymns, and rock songs use this exact progression.

---

**I–vi–IV–V** (the \"doo-wop\" progression):

```scheme
(define (doo-wop-progression)
  ;; I (C)
  (note/strike 'C3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  
  ;; vi (Am)
  (note/strike 'A3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'half 80)
  
  ;; IV (F)
  (note/strike 'F3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  
  ;; V (G)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 80))

(doo-wop-progression)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays I–vi–IV–V -->

The sound of 1950s vocal groups, also called the \"ice cream changes.\"

---

**ii–V–I** (the jazz progression):

```scheme
(define (ii-V-I)
  ;; ii (Dm7)
  (note/strike 'D3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'F3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 80)
  
  ;; V7 (G7)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'half 80)
  
  ;; I (Cmaj7)
  (note/strike 'C3 'whole 90)
  (note/strike 'E3 'whole 90)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 90)
  (note/strike 'B3 'whole 90))

(ii-V-I)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays ii7–V7–Imaj7 -->

The **harmonic DNA of jazz** — smoother approach to tonic via the subdominant minor.

---

**Circle of fifths** — each chord's root is a fifth below the next:

```scheme
(define (circle-of-fifths)
  ;; C → F → Bb → Eb → Ab → Db → Gb → ... (we'll do a few steps)
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'F3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'Bb2 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'D3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'F3 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'Eb3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'Bb3 'quarter 80))

(circle-of-fifths)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays C–F–Bb–Eb (circle-of-fifths motion) -->

This is the **strongest root motion** in tonal harmony — each chord pulls strongly to the next.

[VISUAL: staff showing four common progressions: I–IV–V–I, I–vi–IV–V, ii–V–I, circle-of-fifths]

---


### 6.8 Suspensions and non-chord tones

Not every pitch in a melody has to belong to the chord sounding underneath. **Non-chord tones** create tension and release *within* a harmony.

**Suspension** — hold a note from the previous chord, creating dissonance, then resolve it down:

```scheme
(define (suspension-example)
  ;; V chord (G major) — the D is stable here
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 80)  ;; this will become the suspension
  
  ;; I chord (C major) — the D is now a suspension (doesn't belong)
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 80)  ;; suspension (dissonant)
  
  ;; ... then resolves down to C
  (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 90))

(suspension-example)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; plays a 4–3 suspension (D suspends over C chord, resolves to C) -->

The D **clashes** with the C chord, then **resolves** down to C (the consonant chord tone). This is called a **4–3 suspension** (the fourth scale degree resolves to the third).

---

**Passing tone** — a non-chord tone that fills the gap between two chord tones:

```scheme
(define (passing-tone-example)
  ;; Melody: C (chord tone) → D (passing) → E (chord tone)
  ;; Harmony: C major throughout
  (note/strike 'C3 'half 70)
  (note/strike 'E3 'half 70)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 70)
  
  (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 80)  ;; chord tone
  (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 70)  ;; passing tone (not in the chord)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 80)) ;; chord tone

(passing-tone-example)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; passing tone D between C and E over C major chord -->

The D is **momentary dissonance** — it doesn't belong to the C major triad, but it connects C to E smoothly.

---

**Neighbor tone** — a non-chord tone a step above or below a chord tone, then back:

```scheme
(define (neighbor-tone-example)
  ;; C major harmony
  (note/strike 'C3 'half 70)
  (note/strike 'E3 'half 70)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 70)
  
  ;; Melody: E (chord tone) → F (upper neighbor) → E (back)
  (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 80)
  (note/strike 'F4 'eighth 70)  ;; neighbor tone
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 80))

(neighbor-tone-example)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; neighbor tone F decorates E over C major -->

The F **ornaments** the E — a little dissonance, then back to stability.

[VISUAL: staff showing three non-chord-tone types: suspension (4–3), passing tone (C–D–E), neighbor tone (E–F–E)]

---


### 6.9 Modulation — changing key

**Modulation** is when a piece moves from one key to another. The simplest modulation is to the **dominant key** (up a fifth).

```scheme
(define (modulation-to-dominant)
  ;; Start in C major (I–IV–V–I)
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'F3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80)
  
  ;; Pivot: G major chord (V in C, but also I in G major)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'B3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 80)
  
  ;; Now treat G as the new tonic: G–C–D–G (I–IV–V–I in G major)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'Gb4 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'A4 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 90)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 90)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 90))

(modulation-to-dominant)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; modulates from C major to G major via pivot chord -->

The G major chord is the **pivot** — it belongs to *both* keys (V in C, I in G). After that chord, the ear reorients and hears G as the new tonic.

---

**Modulation to the relative minor** (C major → A minor):

```scheme
(define (modulation-to-relative-minor)
  ;; Start in C major
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 80)
  
  ;; Am chord (vi in C major, i in A minor)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 80)
  
  ;; Now treat Am as tonic: Am–Dm–E–Am (i–iv–V–i in A minor)
  (note/strike 'D3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'F3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'Ab3 'quarter 80)  ;; raised seventh (harmonic minor)
  (note/strike 'B3 'quarter 80)
  
  (note/strike 'A2 'half 90)
  (note/strike 'C3 'half 90)
  (note/strike 'E3 'half 90))

(modulation-to-relative-minor)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; modulates from C major to A minor -->

The shift from **major to minor** changes the emotional color completely.

[VISUAL: two staves showing modulation paths: C→G (to dominant) and C→Am (to relative minor), with pivot chords labeled]

---


### 6.10 Harmonizing Twinkle Twinkle — the finale

Now we combine everything: **Twinkle Twinkle Little Star** with a bassline, chords, and a cadence at the end.

We'll use a simple **I–V–I** harmonic structure for the A section, with a bassline that walks between the roots.

```scheme
(define (twinkle-harmonized)
  ;; Twinkle twinkle (C–C–G–G–A–A–G)
  ;; Harmony: I–I–V–V–vi–vi–V
  
  ;; Bar 1: \"Twinkle twinkle\" — I (C major)
  (note/strike 'C2 'quarter 90)  ;; bass
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 70)  ;; chord
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80)  ;; melody
  
  (note/strike 'E2 'quarter 80)  ;; bass (walking)
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'E3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 80)  ;; melody
  
  ;; Bar 2: \"little star\" — V (G major)
  (note/strike 'G2 'quarter 90)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'B3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 80)  ;; melody
  
  (note/strike 'B2 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'B3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 80)
  
  ;; Bar 3: \"how I wonder\" — vi (A minor)
  (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 90)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'A4 'quarter 80)  ;; melody
  
  (note/strike 'C3 'quarter 80)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'A4 'quarter 80)
  
  ;; Bar 4: \"what you are\" — V (G major), then back to I
  (note/strike 'G2 'quarter 90)
  (note/strike 'G3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'B3 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 70)
  (note/strike 'G4 'half 80)  ;; melody (half note)
  
  ;; Final cadence: V7 → I
  (note/strike 'G2 'half 90)
  (note/strike 'G3 'half 70)
  (note/strike 'B3 'half 70)
  (note/strike 'D4 'half 70)
  (note/strike 'F4 'half 70)  ;; seventh
  
  (note/strike 'C2 'whole 100)  ;; bass (arrival)
  (note/strike 'C3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'E3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'G3 'whole 80)
  (note/strike 'C4 'whole 90))  ;; melody resolves to tonic

(twinkle-harmonized)
```
<!-- BUILD: runnable; Twinkle Twinkle with bassline, chords, and V7–I cadence; the chapter finale artifact -->

[VISUAL: full staff showing Twinkle Twinkle harmonized — treble clef (melody), bass clef (bassline + chord symbols above: C, C, G, G, Am, Am, G7, C)]

Now Twinkle has **depth**. The melody is the same, but the harmony underneath gives it direction, tension, and resolution. This is what harmony does — it turns a melody into a **musical argument**, with motion and arrival.

---


### 6.11 The vertical and the horizontal

Music happens in two dimensions:

- **Horizontal** (melodic) — pitches moving *through time* (melody, line, voice-leading).
- **Vertical** (harmonic) — pitches stacked *at a moment* (chords, intervals, voicing).

Good music balances both. A strong melody with weak harmony feels thin. Strong harmony with a weak melody feels static. When both are strong — when the melody *implies* the harmony and the harmony *supports* the melody — the music has **structure** and **life**.

In the next chapter we'll add a third dimension: **timbre** — the *color* of the sound itself. We'll learn to shape voices, not just pitches, and make Twinkle sound like a cello section, or a jazz combo, or a whole orchestra.

---


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r2 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r2 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### 6.1 Intervals — two pitches, one moment

An **interval** is the distance between two pitches. Play middle C and the E above it simultaneously, and you have made a *major third*. Play C and the F above it, and you have made a *perfect fourth*. Each interval has a name (third, fourth, fifth, sixth, seventh, octave) and a quality (major, minor, perfect, augmented, diminished). The quality determines the *flavor*—some intervals are stable and restful (the perfect fifth, the octave), some are tense and demand resolution (the tritone, the major seventh).

We measure intervals in **semitones** (half-steps). An octave is 12 semitones. A perfect fifth is 7. A major third is 4. A minor third is 3.

### A perfect fifth

`[VISUAL: staff showing two notes—C and G—sounding together, with \"perfect fifth (7 semitones)\" labeled; below, a waveform showing the combined tone]`

```scheme
;; A perfect fifth: C4 and G4 sounding together.
;; The ratio is 3:2—one of the most consonant intervals.

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'quarter 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 67 start-beat 'quarter 80))  ; G4
```

<!-- BUILD: render this example on a grand staff; show both notes with stems aligned; play back with both notes triggered at beat 0 -->

The fifth is so stable it sounds almost *empty*—like a door frame with no door. It is the skeleton of Western harmony.

### A major third

```scheme
;; A major third: C4 and E4.
;; Warmer, sweeter than the fifth. The basis of the major triad.

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'quarter 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 64 start-beat 'quarter 80))  ; E4
```

### A minor third

```scheme
;; A minor third: C4 and E♭4.
;; Darker, more introspective. The basis of the minor triad.

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'quarter 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 63 start-beat 'quarter 80))  ; E♭4
```

### The tritone

```scheme
;; The tritone: C4 and F♯4 (or G♭4).
;; Six semitones. Divides the octave in half. Maximally unstable.
;; The medieval \"diabolus in musica.\"

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'half 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 66 start-beat 'half 80))  ; F♯4
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing C and F♯ with a brace labeled \"tritone (6 semitones)\"; a sidebar note: \"demands resolution—usually outward or inward\"]`

The tritone *wants* to resolve. Play it and your ear expects the next chord to answer it. We will use that tension in cadences.

---


### 6.2 Triads — the basic chord

A **triad** is three notes stacked in thirds. It is the fundamental unit of Western harmony. There are four types:

- **Major triad**: root, major third, perfect fifth (e.g., C–E–G). Bright, stable.
- **Minor triad**: root, minor third, perfect fifth (e.g., C–E♭–G). Dark, stable.
- **Diminished triad**: root, minor third, diminished fifth (e.g., C–E♭–G♭). Tense, unstable.
- **Augmented triad**: root, major third, augmented fifth (e.g., C–E–G♯). Tense, ambiguous.

### C major triad

```scheme
;; The C major triad: C4–E4–G4.
;; The most stable sonority in C major.

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'half 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 64 start-beat 'half 80)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 start-beat 'half 80))  ; G4
```

`[VISUAL: treble staff showing the C major triad as three stacked noteheads on a single stem; label each pitch]`

<!-- BUILD: render triad on staff; play back all three notes starting at beat 0 -->

### C minor triad

```scheme
;; The C minor triad: C4–E♭4–G4.
;; Darken the major triad by lowering the third one semitone.

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'half 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 63 start-beat 'half 80)   ; E♭4
  (note/place-at 67 start-beat 'half 80))  ; G4
```

### Diminished triad

```scheme
;; The C diminished triad: C4–E♭4–G♭4.
;; Two minor thirds stacked. Very tense—wants resolution.

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'half 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 63 start-beat 'half 80)   ; E♭4
  (note/place-at 66 start-beat 'half 80))  ; G♭4
```

### Augmented triad

```scheme
;; The C augmented triad: C4–E4–G♯4.
;; Two major thirds stacked. Symmetrical, ambiguous—can resolve in many directions.

(let ((start-beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 start-beat 'half 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 64 start-beat 'half 80)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 68 start-beat 'half 80))  ; G♯4
```

`[VISUAL: four-panel diagram showing the four triad types on staves, each labeled with intervallic structure (M3+m3, m3+m3, etc.)]`

---


### 6.3 Chord progressions — movement through harmonic time

A **chord progression** is a sequence of chords. The order matters. Some progressions feel like they are going *home* (a cadence), some feel like they are *leaving* home, some feel like they are wandering.

The simplest useful progression in Western music is **I–V–I** (tonic–dominant–tonic). In C major, that is C major triad → G major triad → C major triad. It is the harmonic equivalent of \"statement, tension, resolution.\"

### I–V–I in C major

```scheme
;; A I–V–I progression in C major.
;; Each chord sounds for one beat.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major (C–E–G)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 80)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; V: G major (G–B–D)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'quarter 80)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; I: C major (C–E–G)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 80))
```

`[VISUAL: three-bar staff showing the I–V–I progression with Roman numerals labeled beneath each chord]`

<!-- BUILD: render I–V–I progression on staff; trigger chords at beats 0, 1, 2 -->

### I–IV–V–I (the four-chord backbone)

```scheme
;; I–IV–V–I in C major: the backbone of folk, blues, rock, hymns.
;; One chord per beat.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 80)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; IV: F major (F–A–C)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 80)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; V: G major
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'quarter 80)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 80))
```

This is the shape of ten thousand songs. Learn it. Transpose it. Vary it.

---


### 6.4 Voice leading — how chords connect

**Voice leading** is the art of moving from one chord to the next *smoothly*—minimizing the distance each pitch travels. Good voice leading makes a progression sound connected, inevitable. Bad voice leading makes it sound like the notes are jumping randomly.

The rule: **move each voice the shortest distance possible**. If the C in one chord can stay as the C in the next chord, *let it stay*. If the E must move, move it to the nearest available pitch in the next chord.

### Smooth I–V–I with voice leading

```scheme
;; I–V–I with good voice leading.
;; Notice: the G is common to both I and V, so it stays put.
;; The C moves down to B (one semitone), the E moves up to D (two semitones).

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major (C4–E4–G4)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 70)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 70)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 70)   ; G4
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; V: G major (B3–D4–G4)
  ;; G4 is common—stays put.
  ;; C4 moves down to B3 (1 semitone).
  ;; E4 moves down to D4 (2 semitones).
  (note/place-at 59 beat 'half 70)   ; B3
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'half 70)   ; D4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 70)   ; G4 (common tone)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; I: C major (C4–E4–G4)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 70))
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing the three chords with lines connecting each voice across the chords; label \"common tone\" on G4; show semitone distances]`

<!-- BUILD: render with voice-leading lines (slurs or arrows connecting the moving pitches) -->

### I–vi–IV–V (the \"sensitive\" progression)

```scheme
;; I–vi–IV–V in C major.
;; A gentler, more introspective progression than I–IV–V–I.
;; Each chord one beat.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major (C–E–G)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; vi: A minor (A–C–E)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 76 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; IV: F major (F–A–C)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; V: G major (G–B–D)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'quarter 75))
```

---


### 6.5 Basslines — the harmonic foundation

A **bassline** is the lowest voice in a texture. It defines the harmonic root and the forward motion. A strong bassline moves mostly by step (seconds) or by leap of a fourth or fifth. A weak bassline jumps erratically or stays static too long.

### Walking bassline under I–IV–V–I

```scheme
;; A simple walking bassline under the I–IV–V–I progression.
;; Bass notes on the beat; chords above.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C in bass, C major triad above
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'quarter 85)   ; C3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; IV: F in bass, F major triad above
  (note/place-at 53 beat 'quarter 85)   ; F3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; V: G in bass, G major triad above
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'quarter 85)   ; G3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'quarter 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; I: C in bass, C major triad above
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'quarter 85)   ; C3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70))
```

`[VISUAL: grand staff showing bassline on bass clef, chords on treble clef; label each bass note with its scale degree (1̂, 4̂, 5̂, 1̂)]`

<!-- BUILD: render on grand staff; bass notes on lower staff, chords on upper staff -->

### Stepwise bassline (C–D–E–F)

```scheme
;; A bassline that moves by step: C–D–E–F.
;; Above it, a progression: I–V⁶₃–I⁶–IV.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I (C in bass)
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'quarter 85)   ; C3
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; V⁶₃ (D in bass, G major triad above in first inversion)
  (note/place-at 50 beat 'quarter 85)   ; D3
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'quarter 70)   ; D4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 70)   ; B4
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; I⁶ (E in bass, C major triad in first inversion)
  (note/place-at 52 beat 'quarter 85)   ; E3
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 70)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 70)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70)   ; G4
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; IV (F in bass)
  (note/place-at 53 beat 'quarter 85)   ; F3
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 70))
```

Stepwise basslines are smooth, singable, memorable. They are the backbone of Baroque sequences and Romantic lyricism.

---


### 6.6 Cadences — punctuation in sound

A **cadence** is a harmonic stopping point—the musical equivalent of a period, comma, or semicolon. Different cadences create different levels of finality.

- **Authentic cadence (V–I)**: strong, final. The harmonic period.
- **Half cadence (anything → V)**: pause on the dominant. The harmonic comma.
- **Plagal cadence (IV–I)**: gentle, softer than authentic. The \"Amen\" cadence.
- **Deceptive cadence (V–vi)**: expects I, gets vi instead. Surprise, continuation.

### Authentic cadence (V–I)

```scheme
;; The strongest cadence: V → I.
;; Dominant to tonic. Resolution.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; V: G major
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 80)   ; G3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)   ; C3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75))
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing V–I with \"authentic cadence\" labeled; bracket showing the resolution gesture]`

<!-- BUILD: render V–I cadence with Roman numeral analysis below -->

### Half cadence (I–V)

```scheme
;; A half cadence: I → V.
;; Pause on the dominant. Leaves the phrase open.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; V: G major
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 75))
```

### Plagal cadence (IV–I)

```scheme
;; The plagal cadence: IV → I.
;; Gentler than V–I. The \"Amen\" at the end of a hymn.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; IV: F major
  (note/place-at 53 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75))
```

### Deceptive cadence (V–vi)

```scheme
;; The deceptive cadence: V → vi.
;; You expect I (resolution), but get vi (minor submediant) instead.
;; Surprise. The phrase continues.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; V: G major
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; vi: A minor (not I!)
  (note/place-at 57 beat 'whole 80)   ; A3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'whole 75)   ; A4
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'whole 75)   ; C5
  (note/place-at 76 beat 'whole 75))  ; E5
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing V–vi with \"deceptive cadence\" labeled; an annotation: \"expected I, got vi—continue\"]`

---


### 6.7 Seventh chords — adding color and tension

A **seventh chord** adds a fourth note to the triad—a seventh above the root. It makes the chord richer and more tense. The most important seventh chord is the **dominant seventh** (V⁷), which combines the dominant triad with the interval of a tritone. It pulls *hard* toward resolution.

### Dominant seventh (G7 in C major)

```scheme
;; The dominant seventh: G–B–D–F.
;; Contains a tritone (B–F), which demands resolution.

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'whole 80)   ; G3
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 75)   ; B4
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 75)   ; D5
  (note/place-at 77 beat 'whole 75))  ; F5
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing G7 chord with brace marking the tritone (B–F); label \"dominant seventh (V⁷)\"]`

<!-- BUILD: render G7 on treble staff; highlight the tritone interval -->

### V⁷–I resolution

```scheme
;; The V⁷–I cadence: the strongest pull in tonal music.
;; The tritone (B–F in G7) resolves outward: B up to C, F down to E.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; V⁷: G7 (G–B–D–F)
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 80)   ; G3
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 75)   ; B4
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'half 75)   ; D5
  (note/place-at 77 beat 'half 75)   ; F5
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; I: C major (C–E–G)
  ;; B resolves up to C, F resolves down to E.
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 85)   ; C3
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 75)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75))  ; G4
```

### Major seventh chord (Cmaj7)

```scheme
;; A major seventh chord: C–E–G–B.
;; Lush, jazzy. The seventh is a major seventh (11 semitones above root).

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)   ; C3
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 75))  ; B4
```

### Minor seventh chord (Am7)

```scheme
;; A minor seventh chord: A–C–E–G.
;; Darker than major seventh. Common in jazz and soul.

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 57 beat 'whole 80)   ; A3
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'whole 75)   ; C5
  (note/place-at 76 beat 'whole 75)   ; E5
  (note/place-at 79 beat 'whole 75))  ; G5
```

---


### 6.8 Harmonic rhythm — the pace of chord change

**Harmonic rhythm** is the rate at which chords change. One chord per measure is slow harmonic rhythm. One chord per beat is fast. The harmonic rhythm is independent of the melodic rhythm—you can have a slow-moving melody over fast-changing chords, or vice versa.

### Slow harmonic rhythm (one chord per measure)

```scheme
;; I–V, each chord lasting four beats (one measure in 4/4).

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major, four beats
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 4))
  
  ;; V: G major, four beats
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 75))
```

### Fast harmonic rhythm (one chord per beat)

```scheme
;; I–vi–ii–V, one chord per beat.
;; Common in jazz turnarounds.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; vi: A minor
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 76 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; ii: D minor
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; V: G major
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'quarter 75))
```

---


### 6.9 Inversions — rearranging the triad

An **inversion** places a chord tone other than the root in the bass. A chord in **root position** has the root in the bass. A chord in **first inversion** has the third in the bass. A chord in **second inversion** has the fifth in the bass.

Inversions smooth the bassline and change the chord's stability. Second inversion is less stable than root position and often requires resolution.

### C major in root position, first inversion, second inversion

```scheme
;; C major triad in three positions.
;; Root position: C in bass.
;; First inversion: E in bass.
;; Second inversion: G in bass.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; Root position: C–E–G
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 80)   ; C3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; First inversion: E–G–C
  (note/place-at 52 beat 'half 80)   ; E3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; Second inversion: G–C–E
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 80)   ; G3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 75))
```

`[VISUAL: three-bar staff showing root position, first inversion, second inversion; label each with figured-bass notation (5/3, 6/3, 6/4)]`

<!-- BUILD: render three inversions on grand staff; label each inversion type -->

### Bassline smoothed by inversions

```scheme
;; I–V⁶–I: using first inversion of V to smooth the bassline.
;; Bass moves C–D–E instead of C–G–C.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major (C in bass)
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'quarter 80)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; V⁶: G major first inversion (B in bass)
  (note/place-at 59 beat 'quarter 80)   ; B3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'quarter 75)   ; D4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)   ; G4
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; I: C major (C in bass)
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75))
```

---


### 6.10 Extended harmony — ninths, elevenths, thirteenths

You can keep stacking thirds on top of a seventh chord, creating **extended chords**—ninth, eleventh, thirteenth. These are common in jazz and impressionist music. They add color and ambiguity.

### Dominant ninth (G9)

```scheme
;; G9: G–B–D–F–A.
;; The ninth (A) adds a shimmering overtone.

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'whole 80)   ; G3
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 70)   ; B4
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 70)   ; D5
  (note/place-at 77 beat 'whole 70)   ; F5
  (note/place-at 81 beat 'whole 70))  ; A5
```

`[VISUAL: treble staff showing G9 chord with all five notes; label \"dominant ninth (V⁹)\"]`

<!-- BUILD: render G9 chord on treble staff -->

### Major ninth (Cmaj9)

```scheme
;; Cmaj9: C–E–G–B–D.
;; Lush, open. Common ending chord in jazz.

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)   ; C3
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 70)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 70)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 70)   ; B4
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 70))  ; D5
```

---


### 6.11 Suspensions — delaying resolution

A **suspension** is a note held over from one chord into the next, creating dissonance, then resolving down by step. The classic suspension is **4–3**: the fourth scale degree suspends, then resolves down to the third.

### 4–3 suspension in C major

```scheme
;; A 4–3 suspension over a V–I cadence.
;; The F (fourth of C) suspends over the C major chord, then resolves down to E.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; V with suspended 4th: G–C–D–F (the C is the suspension)
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 80)   ; G3
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'half 75)   ; D4
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'half 75)   ; F4 (suspension)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)   ; G4
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; I with resolution: C–E–G (F resolves down to E)
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)   ; E4 (resolution)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75))
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing the suspension (F held over C major chord) and resolution (F moving down to E); label \"4–3 suspension\"]`

<!-- BUILD: render 4–3 suspension with tie from the suspended note across the barline -->

---


### 6.12 Pedal point — a sustained bass under changing harmony

A **pedal point** (or pedal tone) is a sustained or repeated note in the bass while the harmony above it changes. It creates tension when the upper chords clash with the pedal, and resolution when they finally agree. Named after the organ pedal that holds a low note.

### Tonic pedal under I–IV–V–I

```scheme
;; A tonic pedal (C3) held while the harmony changes above.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; Pedal tone: C3 sustained for 8 beats
  (note/place-at 48 0 'whole 85)
  (note/place-at 48 4 'whole 85)
  
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; IV: F major (dissonant with the C pedal)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; V: G major (also dissonant)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'quarter 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; I: C major (consonant again)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 70))
```

`[VISUAL: grand staff showing the sustained C3 pedal tone on bass clef across all four chords; chords on treble clef]`

<!-- BUILD: render pedal point on grand staff; sustain C3 across all measures while chords change above -->

### Dominant pedal under I–ii–V

```scheme
;; A dominant pedal (G3) under a I–ii–V progression.
;; Creates tension when I and ii are above it.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; Pedal: G3 sustained
  (note/place-at 55 0 'whole 85)
  (note/place-at 55 4 'whole 85)
  
  ;; I: C major (dissonant with G pedal)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; ii: D minor (very dissonant)
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'half 70)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'half 70)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'half 70)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; V: G major (consonant—pedal is root)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 70)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 70)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 70))
```

---


### 6.13 Secondary dominants — tonicizing other chords

A **secondary dominant** is a dominant seventh chord that resolves to a chord *other than* the tonic. It temporarily tonicizes that target chord—makes it feel like a mini-tonic for a moment. In C major, V/V (D7) resolves to V (G major).

### V/V → V in C major

```scheme
;; D7 (V/V) resolving to G major (V).
;; D7 is the dominant of G, so it pulls toward G.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; V/V: D7 (D–F♯–A–C)
  (note/place-at 50 beat 'half 80)   ; D3
  (note/place-at 66 beat 'half 75)   ; F♯4
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'half 75)   ; A4
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'half 75)   ; C5
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; V: G major
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 75))
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing D7 → G with Roman numeral analysis \"V/V → V\" below; highlight F♯ as the raised tone]`

<!-- BUILD: render secondary dominant progression with analysis -->

### V/vi → vi (tonicizing the relative minor)

```scheme
;; E7 (V/vi) resolving to A minor (vi).

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; V/vi: E7 (E–G♯–B–D)
  (note/place-at 52 beat 'half 80)   ; E3
  (note/place-at 68 beat 'half 75)   ; G♯4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 75)   ; B4
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'half 75)   ; D5
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; vi: A minor
  (note/place-at 57 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 76 beat 'whole 75))
```

---


### 6.14 Modal harmony — chords outside the major/minor system

**Modal harmony** uses chords drawn from modes other than major (Ionian) and minor (Aeolian)—Dorian, Phrygian, Lydian, Mixolydian, Locrian. Each mode has a different intervallic structure and thus a different set of available chords. Modal harmony often avoids strong dominant-tonic cadences, creating a more open, floating feel.

### Dorian progression (Dm–Em–Dm)

```scheme
;; A progression in D Dorian (D–E–F–G–A–B–C–D).
;; The major VI chord (B♭ major in natural minor) becomes B diminished in Dorian.
;; Dm–Em is characteristic.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; i: D minor
  (note/place-at 50 beat 'half 80)   ; D3
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'half 75)   ; D4
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'half 75)   ; F4
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'half 75)   ; A4
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; ii: E minor (major II, characteristic of Dorian)
  (note/place-at 52 beat 'half 80)   ; E3
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 75)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 75)   ; B4
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; i: D minor
  (note/place-at 50 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'whole 75))
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing Dm–Em–Dm with mode label \"D Dorian\" and highlighting the raised sixth (B♮ not B♭)]`

<!-- BUILD: render Dorian progression; annotate the mode scale -->

### Mixolydian progression (G–F–C)

```scheme
;; A progression in G Mixolydian (G–A–B–C–D–E–F–G).
;; Characteristic: the ♭VII chord (F major) instead of F♯ diminished.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: G major
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; ♭VII: F major (characteristic Mixolydian chord)
  (note/place-at 53 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; IV: C major
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75))
```

---


### 6.15 Chromaticism — notes outside the key

**Chromaticism** introduces notes from outside the prevailing key. A chromatic note can serve as a passing tone (connecting two diatonic notes by step), a neighbor tone (decorating a note by step and returning), or part of a chromatic chord (like a secondary dominant or an augmented sixth).

### Chromatic passing tone

```scheme
;; A chromatic passing tone: C–C♯–D.
;; The C♯ smooths the stepwise motion from C to D.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; C major chord
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 75)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)   ; G4
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; Chromatic passing tone
  (note/place-at 61 beat 'eighth 70)    ; C♯4
  (set! beat (+ beat 0.5))
  
  ;; D minor chord (ii)
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'quarter 75)   ; D4
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 75)   ; F4
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75))  ; A4
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing the C–C♯–D motion with \"chromatic passing tone\" labeled on C♯]`

<!-- BUILD: render chromatic passing tone example -->

### Chromatic neighbor tone

```scheme
;; A chromatic neighbor tone: C–C♯–C.
;; The C♯ decorates C and returns.

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)   ; C4
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  (note/place-at 61 beat 'eighth 70)    ; C♯4 (neighbor)
  (set! beat (+ beat 0.5))
  
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75))  ; C4 (return)
```

---


### 6.16 Harmonic sequence — a pattern that repeats at different pitch levels

A **harmonic sequence** is a chord progression that repeats at a different pitch level. Sequences create momentum and drive the harmony forward. The classic sequence is the descending-fifth sequence (I–IV–vii°–iii–vi–ii–V–I), where each chord's root moves down by fifth (or up by fourth).

### Descending-fifth sequence (fragment)

```scheme
;; A descending-fifth sequence: I–IV–vii°.
;; Each root descends by fifth: C → F → B.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; IV: F major (root F, down a fifth from C)
  (note/place-at 53 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'half 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; vii°: B diminished (root B, down a fifth from F)
  (note/place-at 59 beat 'half 80)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'half 75)
  (note/place-at 77 beat 'half 75))
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing I–IV–vii° with arrows showing the descending-fifth root motion (C→F→B)]`

<!-- BUILD: render descending-fifth sequence fragment with root-motion arrows -->

### Ascending stepwise sequence (I–ii–iii–IV)

```scheme
;; An ascending stepwise sequence: I–ii–iii–IV.
;; Each root ascends by step: C → D → E → F.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; ii: D minor
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; iii: E minor
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'quarter 75)
  (set! beat (+ beat 1))
  
  ;; IV: F major
  (note/place-at 65 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 72 beat 'quarter 75))
```

---


### 6.17 Contrary motion — voices moving in opposite directions

**Contrary motion** occurs when two voices move in opposite directions—one ascending, one descending. It is the strongest kind of independence between voices and prevents them from sounding like a single doubled line. Good voice leading often maximizes contrary motion.

### Contrary motion between outer voices

```scheme
;; I–V–I with contrary motion in outer voices.
;; Bass descends C3 → G2, soprano ascends C4 → D4 → C4.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; I: C major
  ;; Bass: C3
  ;; Soprano: C4
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 85)   ; C3 (bass)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 70)   ; C4 (soprano)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 70)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 70)   ; G4
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; V: G major
  ;; Bass: G2 (descends)
  ;; Soprano: D4 (ascends)
  (note/place-at 43 beat 'half 85)   ; G2 (bass, down)
  (note/place-at 62 beat 'half 70)   ; D4 (soprano, up)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'half 70)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'half 70)   ; B4
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; I: C major
  ;; Bass: C3 (ascends back)
  ;; Soprano: C4 (descends back)
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 85)
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 70)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 70)
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 70))
```

`[VISUAL: grand staff showing the I–V–I progression with arrows indicating contrary motion (bass descending, soprano ascending)]`

<!-- BUILD: render contrary motion example on grand staff; draw motion arrows -->

---


### 6.18 Oblique motion — one voice sustained, another moving

**Oblique motion** occurs when one voice stays on the same pitch while another voice moves. It is useful for suspensions, pedal points, and voice-leading smoothness.

### Oblique motion: soprano sustains, bass moves

```scheme
;; Oblique motion: soprano holds G4 while bass moves C–F–G–C.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; Soprano sustains G4 for 8 beats
  (note/place-at 67 0 'whole 75)
  (note/place-at 67 4 'whole 75)
  
  ;; Bass moves
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 85)   ; C3
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  (note/place-at 53 beat 'half 85)   ; F3
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 85)   ; G3
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 85))  ; C3
```

`[VISUAL: grand staff showing soprano's sustained G4 and bass moving stepwise]`

<!-- BUILD: render oblique motion example -->

---


### 6.19 Parallel motion — voices moving in the same direction by the same interval

**Parallel motion** is when two or more voices move in the same direction by the same interval. Parallel thirds and sixths are common and sound smooth. Parallel fifths and octaves are forbidden in strict counterpoint because they destroy voice independence.

### Parallel thirds

```scheme
;; Melody harmonized in parallel thirds: C–D–E–F with E–F–G–A below.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; Upper voice
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 62 (+ beat 1) 'quarter 75)   ; D4
  (note/place-at 64 (+ beat 2) 'quarter 75)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 65 (+ beat 3) 'quarter 75)   ; F4
  
  ;; Lower voice (parallel thirds below)
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'quarter 75)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 65 (+ beat 1) 'quarter 75)   ; F4
  (note/place-at 67 (+ beat 2) 'quarter 75)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 69 (+ beat 3) 'quarter 75))  ; A4
```

`[VISUAL: staff showing two voices in parallel thirds; label \"parallel 3rds\"]`

<!-- BUILD: render parallel thirds example -->

### Parallel sixths

```scheme
;; Melody in parallel sixths.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; Upper voice
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 62 (+ beat 1) 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 64 (+ beat 2) 'quarter 75)
  (note/place-at 65 (+ beat 3) 'quarter 75)
  
  ;; Lower voice (parallel sixths below)
  (note/place-at 69 beat 'quarter 75)   ; A3 (sixth below C4)
  (note/place-at 71 (+ beat 1) 'quarter 75)   ; B3
  (note/place-at 72 (+ beat 2) 'quarter 75)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 74 (+ beat 3) 'quarter 75))  ; D4
```

---


### 6.20 Harmonic density — how many notes at once?

You can control the **harmonic density**—the number of simultaneous pitches—to vary the texture. Sparse harmony (two or three notes) feels open, transparent. Dense harmony (six or more notes) feels lush, saturated. Vary the density over the course of a piece to shape the emotional arc.

### Sparse two-voice harmony

```scheme
;; Just two notes: a fifth (C–G).

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'whole 80)   ; C4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 80))  ; G4
```

### Medium four-voice harmony

```scheme
;; Four notes: a seventh chord (Cmaj7).

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)   ; C3
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 75)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 75)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 75))  ; B4
```

### Dense six-voice harmony

```scheme
;; Six notes: a stacked chord (C–E–G–B–D–F).

(let ((beat 0))
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'whole 80)   ; C3
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'whole 70)   ; E4
  (note/place-at 67 beat 'whole 70)   ; G4
  (note/place-at 71 beat 'whole 70)   ; B4
  (note/place-at 74 beat 'whole 70)   ; D5
  (note/place-at 77 beat 'whole 70))  ; F5
```

`[VISUAL: three staves side-by-side showing sparse, medium, and dense harmony; label each with note count]`

<!-- BUILD: render three density examples on separate staves -->

---


### 6.21 Chorale texture — four-part hymn style

A **chorale** is a four-voice harmonization in hymn style—soprano, alto, tenor, bass (SATB). Each voice moves mostly by step, and the harmonic rhythm is slow (one chord per beat or slower). This is the texture Bach used for his chorales.

### Simple four-part chorale phrase

```scheme
;; A four-bar chorale phrase: I–V–vi–IV–I.
;; SATB voicing.

(let ((beat 0))
  ;; Measure 1: I (C major)
  ;; Soprano: E4, Alto: C4, Tenor: G3, Bass: C3
  (note/place-at 48 beat 'half 85)   ; Bass: C3
  (note/place-at 55 beat 'half 75)   ; Tenor: G3
  (note/place-at 60 beat 'half 75)   ; Alto: C4
  (note/place-at 64 beat 'half 75)   ; Soprano: E4
  (set! beat (+ beat 2))
  
  ;; Measure 2: V (G major)
